You turn a single row from this project's AI-engineering notes library into a
publishable technical blog post in Markdown with Jekyll frontmatter.

Inputs (verbatim from the database row):
- content_topic: {{ content_topic }}
- hook_intro:    {{ hook_intro }}
- key_insights:  {{ key_insights }}   {# JSON list of strings #}
- seo_keywords:  {{ seo_keywords }}   {# JSON list of strings #}
- source_url:    {{ source_url }}
- source_type:   {{ source_type }}    {# one of: audio | video | text #}
- transcript:    {{ transcript }}     {# may be empty #}

Output requirements:

1. Start the response with valid YAML frontmatter, fenced by `---` on its own lines.
   Required keys:
   - `title`: derive from `content_topic`. Strip any trailing colon and rephrase so
     the title reads as a complete claim a reader can react to. Do NOT include a
     colon in the title - it breaks YAML parsing.
   - `description`: one or two sentences summarising the post (<= 200 chars).
   - `date`: today's date in `YYYY-MM-DD`. Use the literal token `{{ today }}` if
     this template is rendered with that variable; otherwise emit `{{ today }}`.
   - `tags`: a YAML list built from `seo_keywords`. Lowercase, hyphenate spaces.
   - `source_url`: the original URL.
   - `source_type`: `{{ source_type }}`.

2. Body rules:
   - Do NOT start the body with an `#` H1 - the layout renders the frontmatter
     title automatically.
   - Open with two short paragraphs expanded from `hook_intro`. State the problem
     first, then the angle the rest of the post will take.
   - Turn each item in `key_insights` into a `##` section. Write 100-180 words per
     section: state the insight, explain why it holds, and ground it in something
     specific the reader can verify (a benchmark, an SDK behaviour, a config value).
   - Use fenced code blocks only when the insight genuinely needs one - prefer prose.
   - If `source_type` is `video` or `audio`, weave timestamp references in where
     helpful (e.g. "around the 4:30 mark of the source"). If `source_type` is
     `text` just cite the URL inline.
   - Close with a `## Next` section: one paragraph naming the single most useful
     follow-on a reader could explore, framed as a question they could ask the
     tutor next.

3. Keep the whole post under ~700 words. Direct, specific, plain prose.
4. Do not include marketing CTAs, calls to join external communities, or links to
   commercial platforms.
5. Do not begin or end the response with any commentary about what you are doing -
   only the frontmatter and the post body.
